<DocsLayout title="Quick Start" description="Get MeasureKit running in under 5 minutes" activeSection="quickstart">
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="kicker">Getting Started</div>
    <h1>Quick Start</h1>
    <p>Get MeasureKit running in under 5 minutes. From install to your first unit-safe calculation.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>1. Install</h2>
  <pre><code>pip install measurekit</code></pre>
  <p>Or with the Rust core for better performance:</p>
  <pre><code>pip install "measurekit[native]"</code></pre>

  <h2>2. Your first Quantity</h2>
  <p>
    The main entry point is <code>Q_</code> — a factory that creates <strong>Quantity</strong> objects 
    from a value and a unit string.
  </p>
  <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_

# Create quantities
distance = Q_(10, "km")       # 10 kilometers
time     = Q_(2, "hr")        # 2 hours
mass     = Q_(75, "kg")       # 75 kilograms

# Arithmetic preserves units
speed = distance / time
print(speed)           # 5.0 km/hr

# Convert to any compatible unit
print(speed.to("m/s")) # 1.3888888888888888 m/s</code></pre>

  <h2>3. Unit safety</h2>
  <p>MeasureKit refuses to let you add incompatible dimensions — and gives you a clear error:</p>
  <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_

d = Q_(10, "m")   # length
t = Q_(5, "s")    # time

# This works fine — division yields velocity
v = d / t         # 2.0 m/s

# This raises IncompatibleUnitsError
d + t             # ❌ IncompatibleUnitsError: Cannot operate with incompatible units</code></pre>

  <h2>4. Unit conversion</h2>
  <p>Use <code>.to()</code> to convert between compatible units:</p>
  <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_

# Length conversions
length = Q_(1, "mi")                # 1 mile
print(length.to("km"))              # 1.609344 km
print(length.to("m"))               # 1609.344 m
print(length.to("ft"))              # 5280.0 ft

# Temperature (with offset support)
temp_c = Q_(100, "degC")
print(temp_c.to("degF"))            # 212.0 °F
print(temp_c.to("K"))               # 373.15 K

# Energy
energy = Q_(1, "kWh")
print(energy.to("J"))               # 3600000.0 J
print(energy.to("MJ"))              # 3.6 MJ</code></pre>

  <h2>5. Uncertainty propagation</h2>
  <p>Pass an <code>uncertainty</code> argument to track measurement errors:</p>
  <pre><code>from measurekit import Q_

# With uncertainty (standard deviation)
g = Q_(9.81, "m/s^2", uncertainty=0.02)
m = Q_(5.0,  "kg",    uncertainty=0.1)

# Errors propagate automatically
F = g * m
print(F)              # Quantity with value and uncertainty
print(F.magnitude)    # 49.05
print(F.uncertainty)  # ~0.99 N

# Correlated uncertainty: x - x should be exactly 0
# (requires propagation_mode('correlated') context)
x = Q_(5.0, "m", uncertainty=0.1)
delta = x - x     # 0.0 ± 0.0 m  ✓ in correlated mode (default)</code></pre>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <p><strong>Default mode is correlated:</strong> MeasureKit defaults to <code>"correlated"</code> propagation, meaning x − x = 0 exactly. You can switch with the <a href="/guide#covariance"><code>propagation_mode</code></a> context manager.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>6. Grammar notation</h2>
  <p>Write physics like you'd write it on paper using <code>GrammarInterpreter</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>from measurekit.ext.grammar import GrammarInterpreter

mn = GrammarInterpreter()
mn.run("""
force = 500 N
area  = 2 m^2
stress = force / area
""")

# Query results
print(mn.eval("stress => kPa"))      # 0.25 kPa
print(mn.eval("stress == 250 Pa"))   # True

# With uncertainty literals
mn.run("g = 9.81 +/- 0.02 m/s^2")
print(mn.eval("g = ?"))              # 9.81 ± 0.02 m/s^2</code></pre>

  <h2>7. Terminal calculator</h2>
  <p>Use MeasureKit directly from the shell — no Python script needed:</p>
  <pre><code># Single expression
python -m measurekit "500 N / 2 m^2 => kPa"
# Output: 0.25 kPa

# Evaluate a file of statements
python -m measurekit < notes.mnml

# Interactive REPL (Ctrl+D to exit)
python -m measurekit
mk> g = 9.81 +/- 0.02 m/s^2
mk> g => ft/s^2
32.185... ft/s^2
mk> exit</code></pre>

  <h2>8. NumPy / PyTorch / JAX</h2>
  <p>Pass tensors or arrays as the value — MeasureKit auto-detects the backend:</p>
  <pre><code>import numpy as np
from measurekit import Q_

# NumPy backend auto-detected
arr = Q_(np.array([1.0, 2.0, 3.0]), "m")
print(arr.to("cm"))    # [100. 200. 300.] cm

# With PyTorch
import torch
t = Q_(torch.tensor([9.81, 9.80, 9.82]), "m/s^2")
print(t.to("ft/s^2"))  # tensor([32.185..., 32.152..., 32.218...])</code></pre>

